Text.Value: Astarion must have been feasting on her - I was trying to patch her wounds.
Now my moment of wrath is over, I do regret it.
Gods! What the hell is this?
Alfira? Gods - slaughtered like a lamb, in the middle of our camp.
By the gods themselves, what kind of nightmare is this?
Kaincha! This is some sloppy work.
Another waif dead before her time. I wonder how it happened.

EditorData.NodeContext: [Astarion:waking up with the rest of the party to find a dead body in camp, Less sad, more worried that someone could get so close while everyone slept.]

Text.Value: So this wild boar stabbed her around fifty-seven times, I suppose?
There's no way I'd sleep through that. And there's no way a boar killed Alfira.
Chk. Boars are squealing, irritating creatures. I would have heard it.
No boar pursues its prey with such savagery. This was the work of animal, but of a very different nature.
No thumbs on a hoof to hold a dagger.
A boar stabbed her dozens of times? With a knife, no less?
Tell of your amnesia.
The body hasn't even cooled yet. We need to stay alert.
She should not have travelled alone. She paid for her naivety.
Perhaps? I guess all sorts of monsters come out at night.
An animal indeed, to inflict so many cruelties on such an innocent.
Gods. Such a vicious attack, and I slept through her cries.
How did I sleep through that? Gods, poor Alfira. She must've been terrified.
The tadpole is doing this to me, I'm sure.
Maybe... maybe it's the parasite? Messing with your head, like.
The work of the parasite, I reckon.
The parasite must be affecting you deeply.
The work of the parasite, I shouldn't wonder. Bah.
This is not beyond the remit of what the parasite might command.
I have had unusual symptoms from my parasite - perhaps this is a side effect of yours?
I think I must have killed her.
Vow: you will gain control, you will save the next innocent.
*Much is uncertain, but you know one thing for sure: the darkness will strike again, unless you find a light.*
And you're unclean. Why?
And you're covered in blood, but hardly look worse for wear. It isn't yours.
And there you stand, covered in blood, with no idea how it happened?
Now, I can't help but notice that one of us is positively drenched in blood. So...
And it looks like you've been showering in gore. How'd that happen, huh?
Blood stains your skin and your garb. Unmistakable.
You've got blood on you...
You're covered in blood... and it's not yours either, is it?
More importantly, why are you soaked in her blood? It's clearly not your own.
And I can't help but notice that you're positively drenched in blood. So...
You're covered in gore. Why?
You don't scare me. But I'm starting to wonder if I can trust you at all.
It does sound unsettling. Losing control is one thing, but losing your mind? That's something else entirely.
Spill more blood in our camp without reason, and I'll make you fear more than just yourself.
Good. You're still capable of showing that much sense, at least.
Is it the tadpole? Has it taken control of you?
Yeah, it must be the parasite.
*Every one of your instincts screams against the saccharine thought. You feel close to fainting again...*
She attacked me while I was sleeping - I had to!
I... don't know. It could have been the tadpole.
Oh no, you're not pinning this on me. You're the one who found her!
Alfira was no harm to anyone. You know that. She deserved to live.
'Maybe she was evil'? That's how you're justifying this?
Alfira was harmless. Couldn't you have quenched your bloodthirst on something that posed a threat to us?
I don't think even you are convinced by that terrible rationale.
You and I have very different definitions of right and wrong.
Stabbing someone a dozen times can be many things, but 'the right thing' to do? I doubt it.
Listen, darling - you're covered in gore. I know you killed her, I just want to know why.
So what are we supposed to do now? Just wait for your next bout of the forgetsies?
So what next? Pretend this didn't happen and hope you don't go on another amnesic rampage?
So, what are we to do now? We'd be fools to trust you, surely.
I wouldn't trust you with a dinner spoon right now, let alone a blade.
So what exactly are we supposed to do about it? We've enough enemies outside of our camp. We hardly need one within it.
I'm just not sure where this leaves us? It's hard to trust someone who blacks out and stabs you to death.
*One more failed adventurer, gone to the mud now.*
It won't happen again, I promise.
We can but stand guard against the parasite - I'll be watching.
If the parasite is truly to blame, we must be more vigilant than ever and hope this affliction spreads no further. I'm keeping my eye on you.
Even if it was the worm, this was peculiar indeed. I'll be watching.
I don't know whether to hope it was the parasite or not. But we should all be on our guard.
I guess it's the worm. But we can't have this in our camp - got it? Never again. Never ever.
Even if the parasite caused your little 'episode', it had better not happen again. People can't just be murdered in camp - some of us are important.

EditorData.NodeContext: Karlach: With import. This is important.

Text.Value: Really, Astarion? You killed Alfira in our own camp?!
I should've known you couldn't resist a taste, Astarion.
Eugh, the puzzle is coming together... I can just picture it.
I can see it now.
I hate to accuse one of our own. And yet... it makes sense.
I'm not sure I can trust you anymore. But until this thing is out of my head, I'm not sure I can trust myself either.
You promise? You murdered Alfira in cold blood. Forgive me if I'm not confident in your word.
What's a promise worth when the blood you spilled hasn't even dried yet? Pardon my scepticism.
Promises, promises. If you want my trust, you'll make more careful decisions.
Best not to make promises you can't keep. I'll give you the benefit of the doubt, but that's all I have to offer.
It had better not. I don't know if this was the parasite's fault or yours, darling, but I'll keep an extra close eye on you both.
You're not... you're not in your right mind. There's got to be more to it.
As fine a reason as any other, if... unexpected.
That's... it? She annoyed you? If that was just cause for killing someone, I'd be dead a thousand times over. Tell me the truth.
That's all? There has to be something you aren't telling me - out with it.
You can't be serious. What's wrong with you?
I see... That does sound pretty reasonable, actually.
I can't explain it. I am starting to scare myself.
I don't know what happened. I woke up and she was dead.
I suppose I'll set up a few more magical wards around the camp - this dagger-on-sight praxis isn't the most secure of strategies...
And I just slept through it? Hard to believe. But maybe I've been out of the Hells long enough to get some real shut-eye now.
Bah - then we were wrong to let her stay. Better to prevent the disease than to treat it after damage is done.
She could have been here for Gods know what reason. I understand your concern.
She - attacked you? I wouldn't have thought she had it in her. I thought for certain...
Huh, I never knew she had it in her. But if it was self-defence, I suppose we can look past the mess.
Astarion is twitching with anticipation looking at this body - he must have killed her.
*An uneasy feeling lingers in the air.*
I don't know what happened. I woke up and she was dead.
Yes, I did.
She was weak - the world would have killed her sooner or later.
I saw nothing.
You can't be serious. I had nothing to do with this!
Yes, I did.
Remain silent.
If you want to leave me, I will understand.
How can we possibly trust you now?
So, what are we to do now? We'd be fools to trust you, surely.
I wouldn't trust you with a dinner spoon right now, let alone a blade.
And what comes next? Clearly you can't be trusted.
So where does this leave us? It's hard to trust someone who blacks out and stabs you to death.
Tell of your amnesia.
She can't have been dead long - we should be watchful.
She should not have travelled alone. She paid for her naivety.
It is dangerous, wandering around at night. You could bump into anything.
An animal indeed, to inflict so many cruelties on such an innocent.
Thought I'd wake up for something like that. Must be losing my edge. Poor Alfira, gods. She deserved better.
We should do better than this. Be better than this, for those who seek our aid.

EditorData.NodeContext: [Astarion: thinking of his own late-night hunts]

Text.Value: I suddenly woke up in the night, and everything was just like this.
My body acted outside of my control - it was spasming.
This makes no sense. Why here, and why now?
You're starting to scare me too.
It does sound unsettling. Losing control is one thing, but losing your mind? That's something else entirely.
Get hold of your mind, and quickly. I cannot trust those who cannot trust themselves.
Good. You're still capable of showing that much sense, at least.
Is it the tadpole? Has it taken control of you?
*As the inquisition departs, you are left alone with a familiar headache.*
Mourn: you truly wished to journey beside Alfira.
Breathe deeply: you must uncover the cause of your mad spree lest it happen again.
I don't want to say it, but I must: did you do this?
Were you involved in this?
I'm going to say something I'm confident we're all thinking. Was this your doing?
It's time to start talking. What did you do?
You. Talk.
She was brutalised, the killer knifed her many times after she was dead. Was it you?
Please, you're covered in gore. I know you did it - I just want to know why.
You think me a fool? What you suggest is ludicrous. You reek of blood.
I'm going to make the obvious point that you are covered in blood, friend. Point the finger where you will, but you're the one we've caught red-handed.
This blood didn't get there on its own. Her neck didn't snap by any accident.
The blood that stains you betrays the awful truth.
Pointing fingers won't save you. It's clear what happened here.
There'd be no point. We've all got the bug in our heads. It could be any of us. We ought to at least keep an eye on each other.
I'm not ready to turn my back - not yet, anyway. But I need answers. The sooner the better.
And turn you loose on an unsuspecting world? No, I'm not that callous. We stay together for now.
I can take care of myself, if it weren't abundantly clear. Come for my throat and we'll see how long you're left standing.
As tempting a proposition as that is, our fortunes remain intertwined so long as we're still infected. We've no choice but to stick together.
I could, but we have the same parasites - maybe it'll happen to me next. At least together, we can keep an eye on each other.
Gods! What the hell is this?
Alfira? Gods - slaughtered like a lamb, in the middle of our camp.
By the gods themselves, what kind of nightmare is this?
Kaincha! This is some sloppy work.
Another waif dead before her time. I wonder how it happened.

EditorData.NodeContext: [Astarion:waking up with the rest of the party to find a dead body in camp, Less sad, more worried that someone could get so close while everyone slept.]

Text.Value: I think I killed her.
That's... worrisome. If something's messing with your mind, who knows what you'll do next? Could be the work of the parasite, easily.
A very bad sign. The work of the parasite, I reckon.
Different from my own. The work of the tadpole, perhaps.
Bah - a worrying sign. The work of the parasite, I shouldn't wonder.
Amnesia? A side effect of illithid infection, perhaps? Though I've never seen it recorded as a symptom...
That's... unsettling. It could be one of your parasite's games, maybe?
*It appears the lie that passed through your teeth has lifted some fears.*
And this wild boar stabbed more times than I can even count? Please, give me some credit.
Do you take me for a fool?
Chk. Boars are squealing, irritating creatures. I would have heard it.
No boar pursues its prey with such unrelenting cruelty. This was the work of an animal, but of a very different nature.
A boar stabbed her dozens of times? With a knife, no less?
Those are knife wounds, and you know it. A terrifying number of them.
A wild boar ran rampant in the camp and gored her.
Must have been a feral animal. She was long dead when I got here.
*Your guilt is safe, for now.*
I don't think it's a bad look, but it is a very guilty one.
Need I remind everyone that you're the one drenched in gore?
She annoyed me.
Grind your jaw: that was close - you will hide your crime more carefully next time.
You don't remember? How is that possible?
Rubbish. I can't remember half of my life, and you don't see me randomly gutting people. What's really going on?
Look, I know I have a casual relationship with murder - I don't remember everyone I've killed. But I do remember everyone I've killed in the last five minutes.
What do you mean, you don't remember? It just happened!
Shit. You don't remember slaughtering the girl you welcomed to our camp?
What's going on? If something's wrong with you, say it now. This could be your last chance.
This is ridiculous. I get all the blame for a gory murder, but none of the satisfaction of actually killing someone.
Giggle: the only joy greater than murder is to get away with it!
She did come into the camp unannounced. Perhaps I did the right thing, even with the amnesia.
Astarion has his many faults, but he's certainly not wasteful. If this was his kill, he'd have cleaned up the mess.
For once, I'm going to say the vampire is too civilised to do such a thing.
Astarion's no fool. If he dared to feast on the girl, he'd have disposed of the evidence.
Not a single bite mark that I can see. I smell a lie.
I've seen spined devils tear apart cattle with more care. This doesn't look like a vampire's work...
*Something revolts in your churning blood. Why hide what you are? You long to expose yourself.*
I... I can't remember. I don't know why I did it.
I'd never be this wasteful, for a start. Her blood's everywhere.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Astarion indicates the dead and bloody body.

Text.Value: I... I can't remember. I don't know why I did it.
A wild boar ran rampant in the camp and gored her.
I get all the blame for a gory murder, but I still have to go hungry? Ridiculous. Absolutely ridiculous.
Must have been a feral animal. She was long dead when I got here.
Why? Was her innocence just an act?
That much is obvious. But - why?
You 'think' you killed her? You will need to do a lot better than that.
By the Triad, why would you do that?
All right, but why? Her music wasn't that bad, surely?
But... why?
A wild boar ran rampant in the camp and gored her.
You don't remember? How is that possible?
Rubbish. I can't remember half of my life, and you don't see me randomly gutting people. What's really going on?
Look, I know I have a casual relationship with murder - I don't remember everyone I've killed. But I do remember everyone I've killed in the last five minutes.
What do you mean, you don't remember? It just happened!
Shit. You don't remember slaughtering the girl you welcomed to our camp?
You don't remember? Why? What's wrong with you?
It won't happen again, I promise.
I've been on my best behaviour. You all know it.
And this wild boar stabbed her until she resembled a sieve, did it?
Do you take me for a fool?
Chk. Boars are squealing, irritating creatures. I would have heard it.
No boar pursues its prey with such savagery. This was the work of an animal, but of a very different nature.
A boar stabbed her dozens of times? With a knife, no less?
Those are knife wounds, and you know it. A terrifying number of them.
What the hells happened? And how did I sleep through it?
And it was your lovely voice that woke me, so...
You saw something, didn't you?
You're the one who cried out for us. You must have seen something.
You cried out. I hope you can explain yourself.
Did you see something happen? You called for us.
I can't explain it. I am starting to scare myself.
You woke us up - did you see what happened here?
Chk. Here's hoping the explanation is less sloppy than the kill.
You're the one who cried out for us. You must have seen something.
You summoned us. You must know something

Text.Value: Yes, I murdered her.
I think I killed her.
The blood speaks for itself.  Why?
Anyone with half a mind could see that. But - why?
I think that's quite bloody obvious. But why?
By the Triad, why would you do that?
Yes dear, I can see that you killed her. But why did you kill her?
Doesn't exactly take the Fist's best detectives to see that - you're covered in her insides. But why?
*Heh. Heh.*

EditorData.NodeContext: wry chuckle mocking the Dark Urge

Text.Value: I... I can't remember. I don't know why I did it.
*The worm in your head has never slept more peacefully. You know in your heart it was something deeper, hungrier.*
What in the blazes happened to this girl? It's horrible!
Gods! What the hell is this?
By the gods, what horror is this? Who would silence the bard so savagely?
So, the bard's dead. Slaughtered, even.
Kaincha! This is some sloppy work.
Another waif dead before her time. I wonder how it happened.
I see no weapon by her body. What possible threat could she have posed?
So your plan is to gut every young woman who dares to say 'boo'?
She was unarmed, friend. Didn't even have time to draw a weapon.
And yet there's not a scratch on you, while she's... well, scratched rather badly.
You were in fear of your life at the hands of this unarmed bard?
Nonsense. The girl was timid as a mouse, and hardly more dangerous.
Oh, so you were doing her a favour? Well, I'm sure she's very grateful.
She was doomed the moment she joined our camp then. She should have taken her chances out there alone rather than put herself at your mercy.
The weak will be culled by the natural order. Near as I can see, your bloodlust exists outside it.
So you took the initiative and moved things along? How good of you.
A girl like that needs advice, not a dagger in the gut.
She was an artist. A bard. And even if she was nothing at all, she deserved to live.

Synopsis:
Dark Urge wakes up to the corpse of Alfira in camp.
If companions are around, you will have some explaining to do.
NOTE: Always put Astarion in group slot 2  if there are multiple companions
